    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Sarcochilus viridiflorus are made from its flowers, leaves, and roots, which are rich in flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins. An infusion is prepared by steeping the dried flowers in hot water, while a tincture is made by soaking the plant material in a solvent like ethanol or glycerin. Tea is prepared similarly to infusion but often involves a larger quantity of plant material and a longer steeping time, while a salve is a topical preparation made by infusing the plant material in oil. Decoction is a more prolonged process involving boiling the plant material in water to release its active compounds, often used for roots and woody parts that are difficult to infuse. These preparations are used to leverage the plant's potential therapeutic properties, which are being studied for their antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial effects.",
