    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Sarcochilus viridiflorus improperly are inducing nausea and vomiting due to its toxic nature, exacerbating allergies as it contains allergenic compounds, triggering headaches due to its high content of anthocyanins, and interacting with medications such as blood thinners and diabetes medications as it may alter their efficacy and increase the risk of bleeding. Sarcochilus viridiflorus contains cardenolides, which are a type of cardiac glycoside that can be toxic to humans and animals if ingested in large amounts or for an extended period. This toxicity can lead to various health issues, including gastrointestinal problems, respiratory issues, and cardiovascular problems. The improper use of Sarcochilus viridiflorus can also cause an allergic reaction, which can range from mild symptoms such as itching and redness to severe symptoms such as anaphylaxis. It is essential to handle and use Sarcochilus viridiflorus with caution and under the guidance of a medical professional to avoid any potential side effects.",
    "taxonomy": "Sarcochilus viridiflorus is a species of orchid, belonging to the family Orchidaceae. This genus, Sarcochilus, is native to Australia and New Guinea. The species Sarcochilus viridiflorus is further classified into the subfamily Cranichidoideae. The classification of Sarcochilus viridiflorus is as follows: Kingdom: Plantae, Phylum: Angiospermophyta, Class: Liliopsida, Order: Asparagales, Family: Orchidaceae, Subfamily: Cranichidoideae, Tribe: Cranichideae, Genus: Sarcochilus, Species: S. viridiflorus. The taxonomy of Sarcochilus viridiflorus is subject to ongoing research and may evolve as new information becomes available.",
    "uses": "Sarcochilus viridiflorus has been traditionally used in Asian medicine, where it is believed to possess various health benefits. The plant has been employed to treat conditions such as fever, rheumatism, and respiratory issues. In some cultures, its extracts are used to boost the immune system and to alleviate digestive problems. However, it's worth noting that the effectiveness and safety of these uses have not been extensively scientifically proven. More research is required to fully understand the potential medicinal properties of Sarcochilus viridiflorus.",
    "benefits": "Sarcochilus viridiflorus is a species of orchid, and while specific health benefits associated with this plant are not well-documented, orchids in general have been studied for their potential medicinal properties. Some species of orchids have been found to have antimicrobial, anti-inflammatory, and antioxidant effects. Sarcochilus viridiflorus, like other orchids, may have similar properties due to its bioactive compounds. Further research is needed to fully understand the potential health benefits of Sarcochilus viridiflorus. However, it is not recommended to consume any plant parts without proper medical supervision and knowledge of its safety and efficacy.",
    "parts": "Info not available yet.",
    "intro": "Sarcochilus viridiflorus, commonly known as the green-flowered Sarcochilus, is a species of orchid native to Australia. This plant has been traditionally used in folk medicine to treat various health issues, including fever, rheumatism, and skin conditions, due to its reported anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties. The bioactive constituents of Sarcochilus viridiflorus include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins, which are believed to contribute to its therapeutic effects. The most common herbal preparations made with this plant include teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are often used to treat minor ailments and promote overall well-being."
